===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|ermine|lang=enm}}, {{term|ermin|lang=enm}}, {{term|ermyn|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|ermin|lang=fro}}, {{term|ermine|lang=fro}}, {{term|hermine|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|odt|-}} {{m|odt|*harmino}} ‘stoat skin’, from {{m|odt|*harmo}} ‘stoat, weasel’ (compare Dutch dialectal {{term|herm|lang=nl}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*harmô}} (compare Old English {{term|hearma|lang=ang}}, Old High German {{term|harmo|lang=goh}} (adj. {{term|harmin|lang=goh}}, obsolete German {{term|Harm|lang=de}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*ḱormō}} (compare Romansch {{term|carmun|lang=rm}}, obsolete Lithuanian {{m|lt|šarmuõ}}).

Note: The supposed derivation from {{etyl|ML.|-}} {{m|la|mūs}} {{term|Armenius|lang=la||Armenian mouse}} is without any foundation. <ref>{{R:Century 1911}}</ref>

